Minister of Niger Delta Affairs, Godswill Akpabio, has handed over blocks of healthcare centres to Edem Idim Ishiet community in Onna local government area of Akwa State. The minister also handed over completed health centres, classroom blocks, ICT Centre in Oron community in Oron local government area, as well as a primary health centre at Oti-Oro community, in Okobo local government area, including other projects in the state. Handing over the projects at the weekend, Akpabio tasked the host communities to be dedicated in the protection and co-maintenance of the facilities provided by the government. He said the federal government would continue to provide healthcare services to ameliorate the challenges faced by Niger Delta people. health care facilities in their communities. Represented by deputy director, housing and urban development, Ndukwe Ukpai, the minister noted that rural residents often encounter barriers to health care that limit their ability to obtain the care they need. He pointed out that for rural residents to have sufficient access, necessary and appropriate health services must be available and obtainable in a timely manner. According to him, “In pursuance of its statutory mandate, the ministry commenced the construction of ‘Quick Win Intervention projects’ in 2017 as a palliative approach with the goal of improving the life of the people of the Niger Delta region. The construction of the health centre in this region is geared towards making care easily accessible to the communities especially the rural areas”. In a statement by the director of press and public relations in the ministry, Deworitshe Patricia, the  minister described the thorough and timely execution of the projects barely four months after it was awarded in 2020, noting it is the desire of the government that preference would be on people living in the rural areas and the vulnerable population.